    <!-- Main Content -->
    <main class="container mx-auto px-4 py-10 max-w-4xl">

        <!-- Exercise 1-1 -->
        <section class="mb-12">
            <div class="flex items-center mb-4">
                <span class="bg-blue-600 text-white font-bold rounded-full w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center mr-3">1</span>
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800">Exercise 1-1: The Squeeze Theorem</h2>
            </div>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-md p-6 math-card border border-gray-100">
                <div class="mb-6 bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-blue-500">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">Problem Statement</h3>
                    <p>Let $(U_n)_{n \ge 1}$ be defined by: $U_n = \sum_{k=1}^{n} \frac{1}{\sqrt{n^2+k}}$. Show bounds and deduce limit.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="space-y-6">
                    <div>
                        <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-gray-700">1. Proof of Inequality (Encadrement)</h4>
                        <p class="mb-2">We bound the term inside the sum. For any integer $k$ such that $1 \le k \le n$:</p>
                        $$n^2 + 1 \le n^2 + k \le n^2 + n$$
                        <p class="my-2">Taking the square root (increasing function) and then the reciprocal (reverses inequalities):</p>
                        $$\frac{1}{\sqrt{n^2 + n}} \le \frac{1}{\sqrt{n^2 + k}} \le \frac{1}{\sqrt{n^2 + 1}}$$
                        <p class="my-2">Summing from $k=1$ to $n$ (multiply bounds by $n$ since they are constant with respect to $k$):</p>
                        $$n \times \frac{1}{\sqrt{n^2 + n}} \le U_n \le n \times \frac{1}{\sqrt{n^2 + 1}}$$
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-gray-700">2. Convergence and Limit</h4>
                        <p>Calculate the limits of the bounds as $n \to +\infty$:</p>
                        <p class="pl-4 border-l-2 border-gray-300 my-2">
                            Lower bound: $\lim \frac{n}{\sqrt{n^2+n}} = \lim \frac{n}{n\sqrt{1+1/n}} = 1$
                        </p>
                        <p class="pl-4 border-l-2 border-gray-300 my-2">
                            Upper bound: $\lim \frac{n}{\sqrt{n^2+1}} = \lim \frac{n}{n\sqrt{1+1/n^2}} = 1$
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-2 font-semibold text-green-600">Conclusion: By the Squeeze Theorem, $\lim_{n \to +\infty} U_n = 1$.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Exercise 1-2 -->
        <section class="mb-12">
            <div class="flex items-center mb-4">
                <span class="bg-blue-600 text-white font-bold rounded-full w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center mr-3">2</span>
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800">Exercise 1-2: Linear Recurrence</h2>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-md p-6 math-card border border-gray-100">
                <div class="mb-6 bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-blue-500">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">Problem Statement</h3>
                    <p>Given $U_{n+2} = U_{n+1} - \frac{1}{4}U_n$. Using $V_n = U_{n+1} - \frac{1}{2}U_n$ and $W_n = \frac{2^n}{U_n}$ (Corrected: $W_n = 2^n U_n$).</p>
                </div>

                <div class="space-y-6">
                    <div>
                        <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-gray-700">1. Geometric Sequence $V_n$</h4>
                        $$V_{n+1} = U_{n+2} - \frac{1}{2}U_{n+1} = (U_{n+1} - \frac{1}{4}U_n) - \frac{1}{2}U_{n+1}$$
                        $$V_{n+1} = \frac{1}{2}U_{n+1} - \frac{1}{4}U_n = \frac{1}{2}(U_{n+1} - \frac{1}{2}U_n) = \frac{1}{2}V_n$$
                        <p>It is geometric with ratio $q = 1/2$. First term $V_0 = U_1 - 0.5U_0 = 1$.</p>
                        <p class="font-mono text-sm bg-gray-100 p-2 rounded mt-2">Explicit: $V_n = (1/2)^n$</p>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-gray-700">2. Arithmetic Sequence $W_n$</h4>
                        <p>Let $W_n = 2^n U_n$. Calculate the difference:</p>
                        $$W_{n+1} - W_n = 2^{n+1}U_{n+1} - 2^n U_n = 2^n(2U_{n+1} - U_n)$$
                        <p>Notice that $2V_n = 2U_{n+1} - U_n$. Substitute this in:</p>
                        $$W_{n+1} - W_n = 2^n(2V_n) = 2^n \cdot 2 \cdot (1/2)^n = 2$$
                        <p>It is arithmetic with $r=2$. First term $W_0 = -1$.</p>
                        <p class="font-mono text-sm bg-gray-100 p-2 rounded mt-2">Explicit: $W_n = -1 + 2n$</p>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-blue-600 font-semibold">Result for $U_n$: $U_n = \frac{2n-1}{2^n}$</p>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-gray-700">3. Calculating the Sum $S_n$</h4>
                        <p>We want to prove $S_n = \sum_{k=0}^n U_k = 2 - \frac{2n+3}{2^n}$.</p>
                        <p>Split $U_k$ into two parts: $U_k = \frac{2k}{2^k} - \frac{1}{2^k} = 2k(1/2)^k - (1/2)^k$.</p>
                        $$S_n = 2\sum_{k=0}^n k(1/2)^k - \sum_{k=0}^n (1/2)^k$$
                        <p>Using the standard formula $\sum_{k=0}^n kx^k = \frac{x(1-(n+1)x^n + nx^{n+1})}{(1-x)^2}$ for $x=1/2$, we get:</p>
                        <p>$\sum k(1/2)^k = 2 - \frac{n+2}{2^n}$</p>
                        <p>Substitute back:</p>
                        $$S_n = 2(2 - \frac{n+2}{2^n}) - 2(1 - \frac{1}{2^{n+1}}) = 4 - \frac{2n+4}{2^n} - 2 + \frac{1}{2^n}$$
                        $$S_n = 2 - \frac{2n+3}{2^n}$$
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Exercise 1-3 -->
        <section class="mb-12">
            <div class="flex items-center mb-4">
                <span class="bg-blue-600 text-white font-bold rounded-full w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center mr-3">3</span>
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800">Exercise 1-3: Non-Linear Recurrence</h2>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-md p-6 math-card border border-gray-100">
                <div class="mb-6 bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-blue-500">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">Problem Statement</h3>
                    <p>Given $U_{n+1} = \frac{1}{2} + \sqrt{\frac{1}{2}(U_n^2 - U_n + \frac{1}{2})}$. Study $V_n = U_n^2 - U_n$.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="space-y-6">
                    <div>
                        <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-gray-700">1. Geometric Proof</h4>
                        <p>Calculate $V_{n+1}$:</p>
                        $$V_{n+1} = U_{n+1}^2 - U_{n+1} = U_{n+1}(U_{n+1} - 1)$$
                        <p>Note that $U_{n+1} - 1 = -\frac{1}{2} + \sqrt{\dots}$</p>
                        <p>This creates a difference of squares pattern $(A+B)(A-B) = A^2 - B^2$:</p>
                        $$V_{n+1} = \left(\sqrt{\frac{1}{2}(V_n + \frac{1}{2})}\right)^2 - \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^2$$
                        $$V_{n+1} = \frac{1}{2}V_n + \frac{1}{4} - \frac{1}{4} = \frac{1}{2}V_n$$
                        <p class="font-semibold text-green-600">Result: $V_n$ is geometric with $q=1/2$.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Exercise 1-4 -->
        <section class="mb-12">
            <div class="flex items-center mb-4">
                <span class="bg-blue-600 text-white font-bold rounded-full w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center mr-3">4</span>
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800">Exercise 1-4: Homographic Sequence</h2>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-md p-6 math-card border border-gray-100">
                <div class="mb-6 bg-blue-50 p-4 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-blue-500">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">Problem Statement</h3>
                    <p>$U_{n+1} = \frac{6U_n}{1+15U_n}$. Study monotonicity and $V_n = 1 - \frac{1}{3U_n}$.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="space-y-6">
                    <div>
                        <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-gray-700">1. Monotony</h4>
                        $$U_{n+1} - U_n = \frac{6U_n - U_n(1+15U_n)}{1+15U_n} = \frac{5U_n(1 - 3U_n)}{1+15U_n}$$
                        <p>Since $U_n > 1/3$, the term $(1 - 3U_n)$ is negative. The sequence is <strong>decreasing</strong>.</p>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-gray-700">2. Geometric Transformation</h4>
                        <p>We simplify $V_{n+1}$:</p>
                        $$V_{n+1} = \frac{3U_{n+1}-1}{3U_{n+1}} = \frac{3(\frac{6U_n}{1+15U_n}) - 1}{3(\frac{6U_n}{1+15U_n})}$$
                        <p>After algebraic simplification, we find:</p>
                        $$V_{n+1} = \frac{1}{6} \left( \frac{3U_n-1}{3U_n} \right) = \frac{1}{6} V_n$$
                        <p class="font-semibold text-green-600">Result: $V_n$ is geometric with $q=1/6$.</p>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-gray-700">3. Explicit Forms</h4>
                        <p>$V_n = \frac{2}{3}(\frac{1}{6})^n$.</p>
                        <p>Inverting $V_n = 1 - \frac{1}{3U_n}$ gives $U_n = \frac{1}{3(1-V_n)}$.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

